<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Editing PRM Objects
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to edit existing PRM files, adjust geometry, configure object properties, and import OBJ models.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- LOAD EXISTING -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Loading an Existing PRM
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To edit an existing prim, first set the game prim directory from the File Explorer panel.
        Once the directory is loaded, select a PRM from the list on the left. The selected object is
        loaded into the 3D viewport with its existing geometry and textures.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This is the best way to understand how original Urban Chaos PRMs are built. You can inspect
        the point count, face layout, texture assignment, UV regions, object flags, collision
        settings, damage behaviour, and shadow type.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_edit_load_existing_prim.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- GEOMETRY -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Editing Geometry
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Existing PRMs can be edited using the same basic tools used when creating a new prim. You
        can add new points, remove unnecessary points, and create new triangle or quad faces from
        selected points.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        When changing geometry, remember that texturing is assigned to faces. If you delete or
        replace faces, you may need to reassign textures and UV regions afterwards.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Add points</Bold> when you need additional corners or shape detail.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Delete points</Bold> when they are unused or no longer needed.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Create triangles</Bold> when a three-point surface is needed.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Create quads</Bold> when a four-point surface is needed.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Review the face lists</Bold> after changes to confirm the object structure is correct.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_edit_geometry_tools.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- PROPERTIES -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Prim Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Prim Information panel controls how the object behaves in game. These settings are just
        as important as the mesh itself because they determine collision behaviour, damage behaviour,
        shadow style, and special object flags.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_edit_properties_panel.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Collision Type
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Collision Type controls what happens when the object is hit by a vehicle.
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>None</Bold> — no special collision reaction.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Tree</Bold> — the object behaves like a tree and bends over when struck.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Reduces</Bold> — the object shrinks or reduces when struck.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Damage Types
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Damage flags control the visual reaction when the prim is damaged.
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Is Damagable</Bold> — the object can react to impact and lean over when struck.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Explodes</Bold> — the object blows up when struck.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Crumples</Bold> — the object crumples or deforms when struck.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>No Line of Sight</Bold> — affects line-of-sight or transparency behaviour after the object is struck.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Shadow Type
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Shadow Type controls the shadow drawn underneath the prim.
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>None</Bold> — no special shadow.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Box Edge</Bold> — a box-edge style shadow.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Cylinder</Bold> — a rounded/cylindrical style shadow.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Four Legs</Bold> — shadow style for objects with four contact points.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Full Box</Bold> — a full box-style shadow under the object.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Various Object Flags
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Is Light</Bold> — marks the prim as a light-emitting object, such as a street lamp.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Contains Walkable Facets</Bold> — indicates that some faces on the object can be stood on by the player.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Has Glare</Bold> — enables glare-style behaviour, useful for bright ground lights or small glowing objects.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Is Rotating Item</Bold> — makes the prim behave like a rotating pickup item.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Is Tree</Bold> — marks the object as tree-like, including behaviours such as leaves falling when struck.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Env Mapped</Bold> — likely related to environment mapping or reflective rendering. No obvious visible effect has been confirmed in the editor.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Just Floor</Bold> — purpose not fully confirmed. It may relate to floor-only behaviour or placement rules, but no obvious visible effect has been confirmed.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>On Floor</Bold> — intended to snap or align the object to the floor, although it does not appear to work reliably for every prim.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- OBJ IMPORT -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Importing an OBJ File
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        You can import a model created in Blender or another modelling tool by clicking the
        <Bold>Import OBJ</Bold> quick action button and selecting an
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.OBJ</Run>
        file from disk.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        OBJ import is useful because it lets you use a proper 3D modelling tool for the shape, then
        use the Prim Editor for Urban Chaos-specific setup such as face texturing, UV regions, PRM
        flags, and saving to the correct PRM slot.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_edit_import_obj.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        MTL texture import is deliberately not supported yet. This means imported OBJ models do not
        automatically bring in their Blender material assignments. After importing the OBJ, assign
        textures manually from the Prim Editor texture library.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    The engine supports a maximum of roughly 5000 vertices, but most original prims are much smaller.
                    For best performance, keep custom prims low-poly whenever possible.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
